<TEXT>
the soviet unions most prominent literary journal 
wants to publish cancer ward by alexander solzhenitsyn the 
dissident soviet author forcibly sent into exile 14 years ago as a 
renegade and traitor 
if the novel is printed here it would represent a stunning 
turnaround in official treatment of solzhenitsyn 69 and a further 
broadening in the kremlins campaign for glasnost or greater 
openness 
solzhenitsyn the 1970 nobel literature laureate earned world 
renown and his governments opprobrium in the 1970s for his 
chronology of soviet political repression the gulag 
archipelago 
the editor of the novy mir monthly sergei p zalygin said 
monday that negotiations for publishing cancer ward were under 
way but declined to say anything more 
things should become clear in about a week or 10 days 
zalygin said in an interview 
however solzhenitsyns wife natalya was quoted by the new 
york times as saying monday that soviet officials have not 
approached solzhenitsyn about publishing any of his works in the 
soviet union 
the newspaper said her as saying solzhenitsyn would not discuss 
the report but that she was speaking on his behalf and that any 
talk of possibly publishing cancer ward in the soviet union was 
premature to say the least 
as of today monday solzhenitsyn has not received any kind 
of proposal or other overture about publishing his books in the 
soviet union she said in a telephone interview from the couples 
vermont home according to the times 
twenty years ago novy mir had set cancer ward in type but 
abandoned its plans to print the book in 1968 following the arrest 
of several dissidents 
foreign ministry spokesman gennady i gerasimov said last year 
that solzhenitsyn owns the copyright to the novel and that it 
could not be published in a soviet edition without his consent 
solzhenitsyn a former political prisoner was forcibly exiled 
in 1974 and his works were ordered removed from public libraries 
before solzhenitsyns exile the communist party daily pravda 
called the writer a renegade and a profoundly immoral man 
and said he merited the fate of a traitor it said the gulag 
trilogy was another slanderous book from his pen 
since mikhail s gorbachev became soviet leader in march 1985 
many soviet authors whose works were once banned have been 
published in soviet editions including boris pasternaks dr 
zhivago and mikhail bulgakovs heart of a dog 
but solzhenitsyn has remained off limits 
many of the criticisms leveled by solzhenitsyn at the bloody 
political terror waged by dictator josef v stalin have become 
commonplace in soviet media under gorbachev 
in works like the gulag trilogy solzhenitsyn goes beyond 
official soviet thinking by saying that widescale baseless 
repression began under soviet founder vladimir i lenin and that 
rule by the officially atheist communist party leads to immorality 
during the moscow summit president reagan made a speech at the 
official writers union in which he appealed for publication of 
solzhenitsyns works in his native land 
zalygin told reporters then that publication of cancer ward 
was contingent on an agreement with solzhenitsyn and that he was 
conducting the negotiations himself 
in cancer ward solzhenitsyn depicts a hospital in soviet 
kazakhstan at the twilight of stalins 29year reign which ended 
with the dictators death in 1953 the hospital seems to stand for 
soviet society as a whole while the cancer the patients suffer 
from represents the ravages of stalins terror 
cultural bureaucrats reportedly ruled out the publication of 
cancer ward while solzhenitsyn was still living in the soviet 
union because they thought the book antihumanist 
but zalygin said he evaluated the novel in a positive way in 
my opinion this is an interesting and serious work 
in 1967 solzhenistyn engaged in acrimonimous and ultimately 
futile debate with the writers union to push for publication of 
cancer ward 
in a meeting at the writers union headquarters he said the task 
of literature was to tell people the real truth as they expect 
it and to lay bare the secrets of the human heart and 
conscience 
the head of the writers union vladimir v karpov spoke monday 
of the possibility of publishing solzhenitsyn and said the writer 
may even be allowed to return home 
karpov said he did not think an official invitation would be 
extended to solzhenitsyn to return 
karpov and other soviet cultural figures met with reporters to 
discuss the nationwide communist party conference that opens 
tuesday 
solzhenitsyn was arrested in 1945 on the grounds that he had 
criticized stalin and spent eight years in labor camps he was 
released in 1953 and won fame in 1962 when novy mir published his 
chronicle of stalinera prison camp life one day in the life of 
ivan denisovich 
</TEXT>
