<TEXT>
boys who spend part of their childhood in 
oneparent families tend to leave school earlier than those who 
live with both parents according to a new study 
there was much less impact on girls who may be motivated by the 
example of a working mother say researchers sheila fitzgerald 
krein and andrea h beller of the school of human resources and 
family studies at the university of illinoisurbana 
their study which also noted that the impact of oneparent 
living on children is greatest in the preschool years was 
published in demography the journal of the population association 
of america 
a working mother supporting herself and family seems to 
provide a good example for daughters beller said monday in a 
telephone interview 
for girls this model seems to balance out the loss of the time 
and involvement of one parent whereas the boy doesnt have this 
model he just has the loss of a parent 
about 60 percent of all children are now estimated to spend at 
least some of their childhood with only one parent around krein 
and beller reported 
this trend has aroused social concern in part because these 
families typically have fewer resources in particular time and 
moneythan twoparent families they pointed out 
educational advancement is one route out of poverty but the 
children in these families get significantly less of it the 
report says thus this lower level of education will have 
longterm consequences for the economic wellbeing of the future 
family of this young adult 
krein and beller said they studied effects on education because 
it has been shown to be a predictor of welfare recipiency and 
persistent poverty and lack of education is one determinent of 
chronic unemployment 
they used a pair of longterm surveys to study two generations 
of mothers and their offspring totaling 2500 boys and girls 
in general the longer time spent in a singleparent family 
the greater the reduction in educational attainment they found 
the largest impact was among white males they reported with 
each year spent in a oneparent family reducing eventual education 
by about onetenth of a year 
white men who spent an average number of years 51 in a 
singleparent family completed 05 fewer years of schooling than 
those who spent none white men who spent all 18 years in a 
singleparent family completed 17 fewer years of schooling they 
found 
the average number of years with just one parent around was 
found to be 80 years for black males and those in that situation 
finished 06 fewer years of school black males spending 18 years 
with just one parent finished 13 fewer years of school 
the impact was much less significant for women 
indeed for white women time spent in a singleparent family had 
no impact on eventual education there was only a slight impact for 
black women 
a followup study not yet published found that the effect of 
the missing parent is reduced although not eliminated when the 
father pays child support beller said 
in these cases though the father may not be present he still 
serves as a good example and that affects educational attainment 
in positive direction the study said 
the greatest impact on eventual education was among youngsters 
whose preschool years were spent in oneparent families the study 
said years spent in a singleparent family during the elementary 
school and highschool periods have no significant impact 
since the preschool years matter most affordable daycare 
with an educational component could replace some of the functions 
of the absent parent the study says 
living in a family with brothers and sisters thus reducing the 
time available for the parent to concentrate on any one child 
also reduced eventual educational attainment beller and krein 
found again the effect was most pronounced among boys 
factors the researchers found to boost educational attainment 
were higher family income amount of reading materials in the home 
and the mothers education the fathers education appeared to be a 
factor among whites but not blacks they added 
</TEXT>
