an overwhelming majority of americans have a 
negative view of cubas marxist government but slightly more than 
half favor talks with cuba on improving relations according to a 
poll released today 
the survey showed that 81 percent of americans have an 
unfavorable attitude toward cuba compared with 52 percent in 1977 
only 1 percent see cuba in a very favorable light 
but 51 percent would support the united states entering into 
negotiations with cuba looking toward reestablishing normal 
diplomatic and economic relations thirtyone percent are opposed 
to that policy 
the survey was commissioned by potomac associates an 
independent policy research organization at johns hopkins school of 
advanced international studies in washington the polling was 
conducted by the gallup organization 
it was carried out in march and involved interviews with 1038 
adult americans the survey has a margin of error of 4 percentage 
points 
based on the survey if either of the major party candidates 
indicates a readiness to improve relations with cuba his standing 
with the voters would benefit slightly 
