<TEXT>
a commuter train whose brakes apparently failed 
slammed into another train at an underground platform of a busy 
paris station killing at least 37 people and injuring 32 
officials said 
it was the worst train accident ever in the capital authorities 
said the death toll was expected to mount to 40 once all the 
bodies were removed from the twisted wreckage 
officials said the eightcar commuter train coming from the 
southeastern suburb of melun rammed into the front of a fourcar 
train that was preparing to leave an underground terminus at the 
gare de lyon station in eastern paris 
philippe rouvillois president of the railroad authority known 
as the sncf said the moving train had a braking problem and 
its driver alerted passengers to move to the rear 
when the driver noticed a problem with the brakes he asked 
travelers in the train to move toward the back rouvillois said 
he said the train went about 500600 yards past a red light as 
it was approaching the gare de lyon one of the busiest train 
stations in paris the gare de lyon is a stop for the citys 
subways and handles commuter traffic as well as intercity trains 
an unknown number of bodies remained inside the wreckage fire 
officials said they thought all survivers had been removed it was 
not immediately known if any americans were among the victims 
at least 15 people were seriously injured officials said 
passengers in shock wandered through the station or sat on the 
platform beside the twisted wreckage 
about 250 rescue workers struggled through the night sawing 
through the tangle of metal looking for more survivors forty fire 
engines 15 ambulances and a helicopter were at the station 
police said it would be several hours before the last bodies 
were freed they said both trains were crowded with commuters when 
the accident occurred at 710 pm 110 pm edt but the total 
number of passengers was not known 
rescuers pulled the first body from one of the cars about two 
hours after the accident witnesses said the impact of the speeding 
train hitting the one parked on the tracks forced the cars of the 
first train into and on top of one another 
the french news agency agence francepresse quoted railway 
authority officials as saying the inbound train was moving at 45 to 
50 mph when it entered the station 
in addition train authority officials said the train leaving 
paris was several minutes behind schedule 
