<TEXT>
middlemen who profit from surrogate births 
risk up to five years in prison and 50000 in fines under a law 
that makes michigan the first state to attach criminal sanctions to 
pregnancyforpay deals 
gov james blanchard on monday signed into law a bill that makes 
arranging such deals a felony beginning sept 1 advertising or 
otherwise inducing a woman to become a surrogate also will be a 
felony 
its a major victory jeremy rifkin cochair of the 
national coalition against surrogacy said in washington 
michigan will be leading the way with this legislation said 
state sen connie binsfeld leader of a fiveyear drive to outlaw 
surrogacy 
i believe the legislature and the governor have carried out a 
very strong moral obligation to protect children from becoming 
commodities under commercial contracts said the republican 
senator 
the executive director of the american civil liberties unions 
michigan chapter said he was contemplating a legal challenge 
against the law 
its hard to understand how a governor whos prochoice would 
criminalize the process when a surrogate mother and a couple wish 
to bring life into this world said howard simon 
in announcing his decision the democratic governor said he 
signed the law despite reservations because he believed it was 
better than none at all 
by taking the profit out of childbirth it stands firm against 
the buying and selling of human life he said 
also under the law those who contract for a birth and women who 
agree to bear a child for money will risk misdemeanor penalties of 
up to 90 days in jail and a 10000 fine 
typically infertile couples pay 10000 to be matched with a 
wouldbe mother they pay another 10000 to the woman who agrees 
to be artifically inseminated carry the child then give up 
custody they also pay for the hospital bills and pregnancyrelated 
expenses 
the law would still allow a woman who wants to bear a child and 
then give up the baby to another couple to do so while having 
pregnancyrelated bills paid but the mother could get no fee and 
any middleman would have to work for free 
the law doesnt address the legality for a michigan couple to 
sign a contract in another state and carry out the agreement in 
michigan said noel keane a dearborn attorney who has arranged 
228 surrogate births including new jerseys baby m 
maybe the arrangement of a contract could be anywhere outside 
michigan and the insemination the birth the payment everything 
else take place inside michigan said keane 
keane said a constitutional challenge probably would be based on 
a 1972 us supreme court decision establishing as part of the 
right to privacy the right to beget children without unwarranted 
governmental intrusion 
the mother of baby m mary beth whiteheadgould sued keane 
when she decided to keep her child she won an outofcourt 
settlement for an amount reported at between 30000 and 40000 
but in a landmark custody battle over the girl she bore under a 
10000 contract mrs whiteheadgould won only visitation rights 
on feb 3 the new jersey supreme court granted custody of the 
2yearold girl now legally known as melissa to the childs 
father william stern 
the court in overturning part of a lower court ruling also 
outlawed surrogacy for pay and restored mrs whiteheadgoulds 
parental rights to the child 
michigan is the first state to attach criminal penalties to 
surrogateparent contracts but not the first to address the issue 
kentucky and louisiana have enacted laws declaring such 
contracts illegal but dont impose criminal penalties nebraska 
doesnt recognize the legal validity of surrogateparenting 
contracts indiana has put enforcement of such arrangements on hold 
while the issue is researched and proposed regulations were vetoed 
in arkansas 
harold cassidy mrs whiteheadgoulds attorney said states 
generally have not have not enforced those statutes out of 
apparent confusion as to whether such enforcement would represent 
the will of the people he said 
he said many states will follow michigans lead and 
prosecutors will no longer have a choice in bringing charges 
against surrogacy brokers 
