<TEXT>
the key to winning the war on drugs is in 
reducing demand for illicit narcotics by treating users not in 
spending billions to catch smugglers and pushers a report to 
nations largest doctors organization says 
a report by the american medical associations board of trustees 
calls for revamping the nations efforts to combat the drug problem 
by focusing more energy and money on rehabilitating drug users 
many doctors endorsed the proposal during a committee hearing 
monday at the amas annual policymaking convention the committee 
is expected to issue a recommendation today on whether the 
420member house of delegates a legislative body representing the 
amas 295000 members should approve the proposed drug policy 
before the convention ends thursday 
we think this lays out a blueprint for the american people to 
effectively do something about the drug problem said dr lonnie 
bristow an ama trustee and internist from berkeley calif 
we frankly hate to see money just going down the tubes while 
our nation talks about whether we should have the army and the navy 
patrolling the borders to interdict drug sellers 
he said the ama boards report shows the nations 
muchpublicized war on drugs has been a failure because its had 
the wrong focus 
with annual revenues estimated at 30 billion to 100 billion 
drug traffickers have the money to counteract government 
crackdowns the report contends 
they can acquire sophisticated technology bribe public 
officials and recruit new members with such a strong financial 
base these organizations have demonstrated the ability to counter 
each new interdiction strategy 
bristow said as long as we concentrate on the supply end of 
the problem were just pouring money into a sieve 
the ama boards report recommends that the federal government 
expand drug abuse treatment programs ease regulations to permit 
private doctors to treat addicts with methadone and improve drug 
education programs aimed at adolescents 
it doesnt say how much extra money should be spent for these 
efforts 
the report notes that one federal rule makes it difficult for 
addicts to get treatment by generally only admitting to methadone 
programs people who have been addicted to heroin for at least a 
year it recommends modifying the rule to let doctors running such 
programs admit any patient physically dependent on opiates 
the need for new treatment centers is acute the report 
said only about 150000 of the estimated 14 million iv drug 
abusers currently are in treatment 
the proposal also calls on the president to appoint a 
highranking official of the executive branch to coordinate federal 
drug policy to reduce rivalry among different agencies and keep 
them from working at dual purposes 
the ama board reiterated its opposition to widespread random 
drug testing of employees working in private industry 
but it said limited workplace drug testing should be carefully 
evaluated when its done in conjunction with a treatment program 
as part of preemployment screening for jobs affecting the publics 
health and safety or when an employer suspects a workers 
performance is impaired 
the ama board also said it opposes legalization of illicit 
drugs contending such a move would lead to increased drug use the 
report calls the nations renewed efforts to combat the drug 
problem laudable but says they have yet to lead to 
substantial reductions in the use of illegal drugs 
</TEXT>
