<TEXT>
federal health researchers say giving free fans 
to the poor and elderly during heat waves may not be such a great 
idea because fans could actually increase heat stress instead of 
relieving it 
the national centers for disease control has sent state health 
officers an advisory on precautions to take during heat waves 
particularly to safeguard the health of the poor and elderly 
a review of occupational comfort and occupational health studies 
dating back to the 1920s shows that fans may only blow hot air on 
the person whos trying to cool off said dr ed kilbourne of the 
cdc 
as the temperature gets around 100 we find that above that 
increasing air velocity tends to increase heat stress kilbourne 
said in an interview monday 
he stressed that other factors including humidity come into 
play in discussing heat stress 
but under some circumstances where areas are diverting 
resources to hand out fans the money may be better spent in 
getting people to shelters 
the cdc in its weekly report last thursday recommended that in 
times of severe heat special care should be taken to protect 
elderly and poor people particularly innercity residents against 
heatstroke and other illnesses 
for example elderly persons may be taken to an 
airconditioned shopping mall for 23 hours per day the cdc 
suggested 
kilbourne said the cdcs research has cast doubt on one widely 
held notion the idea that air conditioning may make some people 
more susceptible to heatrelated illnesses when they leave the cool 
indoors that appears not to be the case he said 
the cdc studied heatrelated deaths in 1980 when more than 
1700 such fatalities were reported nationwide 
in july 1980 st louis and kansas city mo were among cities 
noticing a sharp increase in deaths during a time of severe heat 
deaths from all causes in st louis were up 57 percent from july 
1979 in kansas city it was 64 percent kilbourne said 
you can double or triple the daily number of people dying 
during a heat wave he said 
