<TEXT>
more than nine years have passed since charles 
mingus the seminal jazz bassist and composer died at age 56 in 
mexico where he was being treated for lou gehrigs disease 
during that time mingus innovative compositions and 
arrangements have been perpetuated in performances by the mingus 
dynasty band an ensemble of varying personnel led by trombonist 
jimmy knepper who played with mingus in the late 50s and 60s 
an expanded version of the mingus dynasty band celebrated the 
late jazz bassist with a joyous jvc jazz festival concert monday 
night at the kaufmann concert hall at the 92nd street y 
although fewer than half the seats in the 926seat hall were 
filled those in attendance got a pleasurable lesson in what made 
mingus such an influential force as jazz moved from bebop into the 
more eclectic styles of the 1960s 
monday nights band combined elements of the old former mingus 
bandsmen jaki byard on piano jack walrath on trumpet john handy 
on alto saxophone and knepper with the young jon faddis on 
trumpet and craig handy no relation to john on tenor saxophone 
mingus lush arrangements in which the horns and saxophones 
weave dense patterns of sound as a backdrop for the soloists were 
as fresh as when he did them more than two decades ago 
the set opened with jump monk mingus uptempo appreciation 
of the late pianist theolonius monk 
another object of mingus affection duke ellington provided 
the inspiration for duke ellingtons sound of love a lovely 
ballad launched with a moving solo by byard 
mingus genius as a composer and arranger came through most 
strongly in stop look and listen an ambitious collection of 
rhythms moods and styles from his acclaimed album on the impulse 
label the black saint and the sinner lady 
rounding out the band was sam burtis on trombone and tuba david 
murray on tenor saxophone nick brignola on baritone sax george 
mraz on bass and billy hart on drums 
mondays concert opened with a courageous set by pianist geri 
allen and her trio the program of original compositions started 
slowly but gradually picked up excitement as the trio warmed to 
the occasion 
although largely in the avantgarde style of polytones and 
polyrhythms ms allens music retained sufficient melodic content 
to hold the audiences interest and she received a warm ovation 
the jvc jazz festival continues in new york through saturday 
</TEXT>
