<TEXT>
at least 50000 hungarians many 
carrying torches and candles marched quietly past the romanian 
embassy to protest a plan to demolish thousands of romanian 
villages 
monday nights rally was the largest unofficial demonstration in 
hungary since an antisoviet uprising was crushed in 1956 police 
protected the embassy compound but did not interfere 
the protest was organized by a dozen opposition and other 
unofficial groups but it was officially authorized by police in 
this communist country 
observers watching the crowd and listening to the slogans 
chanted felt the demonstration was pervaded not only by 
discipline the knowledge of representing a just cause but an 
awareness of central european consciousness the government 
newspaper magyar hirlap said today 
before the march to the embassy about 30000 people gathered on 
downtown heroes square to hear speeches denouncing the forcible 
resettlement plan according to the official hungarian news agency 
mti 
the proposed plan to raze about 7000 of romanias 13000 
villages which would affect hundreds of communities of people of 
hungarian and german heritage has strained hungarianromanian 
relations 
the demonstration reflected the anxiety hungarian society 
feels about the fate of the villages in romania and the fact that 
it is not accepting that bulldozer policy as a government policy 
in these concluding years of the 20th century 
unofficial demonstrations of up to 15000 people have been held 
before but they were never sanctioned and sometimes dispersed by 
force 
smaller unofficial demonstrations have been staged in hungary 
before but they were never sanctioned and sometimes dispersed by 
force 
the crowd moved slowly past shouting protests then marched 
back to the square laying flowers at monuments to hungarian kings 
they also heard a message of solidarity from lech walesa the 
leader of the banned polish free trade union movement solidarity 
banners denounced the resettlement and scores of demonstrators 
held up signs of place names in hungarian german and romanian that 
they fear will vanish from the map 
in march president nicolae ceausescu of romania announced plans 
for demolishing 7000 villages which would be replaced by big 
agriculturalindustrial centers 
romanian staterun media have said the program aims to gain more 
farmland for use by the countrys collectivized agriculture which 
is plagued by lack of incentives for farmers and livestock fodder 
shortages 
the forced resettlement program would affect hundreds of 
villages of romanias 17 million ethnic hungarians who complain 
of official discrimination and say they are denied ethnic and 
cultural rights 
a manifesto read to mondays crowd said after 50 years there 
is another criminal committing genocide 
hungarian intellectuals have denounced as genocide both the 
project for demolishing villages and romanias alleged policy of 
discrimination against ethnic hungarians 
mondays manifesto also referred to the mass murder of jews and 
other civilians committed by the nazis before and during world war 
ii 
the document was written by istvan csurka a prominent hungarian 
opposition writer and read by actor istvan bubik it combined 
appeals for restraint and for solidarity with ethnic hungarians in 
romania 
csurka appealed to hungarians to show solidarity and 
determination in trying to prevent what the magyar nemzet newspaper 
earlier monday called romanias bulldozer revolution 
relations between neighboring warsaw pact nations have 
deteriorated rapidly over the issue of ethnic hungarians 
