<TEXT>
a joint committee of the navy and 
environmental groups today unveiled recommendations on how the navy 
can stop dumping plastic trash at sea 
the navy has begun carrying out some of the recommendations for 
instance a contract to buy 11 million small plastic bags for use 
by ships stores has been canceled said the report of the group 
led by the keystone center an organization based in keystone 
colo that mediates environmental disputes 
under legislation passed late last year to carry out an 
international treaty the navy is supposed to stop dumping plastic 
trash at sea in five years 
environmentalists see plastics as a growing killer of birds and 
other marine life nondegradable bags sixpack loops and other 
plastics can entangle birds or be eaten by them and other organisms 
the committee of navy personnel environmentalists and members 
of congressional staffs was convened last october and immediately 
started visiting ships including an aircraft carrier in the 
mediterranean 
the recommendations call for among other things studies to 
identify food for which packaging other than plastic is available 
surveying waste of ships at sea and ordering test packages of other 
materials changing to those materials where possible installing 
trash compactors separation and storage of plastics while at sea 
unloading as much trash as possible before leaving port and support 
for development of degradable packages 
navy ships bring trash back to port if operating less than 25 
miles from shore but throw it overboard when further out to sea 
the navy is supposed to report to congress in three years on 
what problems it has in eliminating plastic trash 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

