<TEXT>
the reagan administration on tuesday urged 
speedy senate ratification of two treaties negotiated in the 
aftermath of the explosion at the chernobyl nuclear power plant in 
the soviet union which spread nuclear contamination across western 
europe 
one treaty requires prompt notification of a nuclear disaster 
which has the potential of affecting other nations the second sets 
up a system for providing assistance after a nuclear accident 
frederick m bernthal assistant secretary of state for 
scientific affairs told the senate foreign relations committee the 
objective of the pacts is to minimize the radiological 
consequences of a nuclear accident should one occur 
he said the treaties stem from the international concern over 
the failure of the soviet union to notify the rest of the world 
in a timely manner after the accident at chernobyl 
the treaties were drafted in a fourweek period in the summer of 
1986 by a conference of 62 nations meeting in vienna 
the notification treaty covers accidents at nuclear reactors 
nuclear fuel cycle facilities and radioactive waste management 
facilities 
it also covers accidents involving the transport and storage of 
nuclear fuels or radioactive waste as well as radioisotopes used to 
generate power in space objects of any kind 
accidents involving nuclear weapons are not covered by the 
treaty but a provision does encourage nations to volunteer 
information on nuclear weapons accidents 
the united states has pledged to voluntarily provide 
notification on any nuclear accident including accidents 
involving nuclear weapons 
the second treaty provides guidelines on the provision of 
technical assistance to minimize the effects of nuclear accidents 
while it does not require any country to provide such 
assistance it does require a prompt response to requests for such 
help 
the administration also asked ratification of a third treaty 
intended to protect a western seat on the board of governors of the 
international atomic energy agency 
bernthal said the change became necessary when the peoples 
republic of china became a member of the international atomic 
energy agency and claimed a seat on the board of directors 
bernthal said chinas inclusion on the board of governors could 
have put a western seat at risk 
it is important to us national security not to dilute 
western influence on the iaea board bernthal said 
the treaty would expand the number of seats on the board by one 
and would put all countries back in their starting position 
bernthal said in short ratification of this amendment will 
protect a western seat 
</TEXT>
