<TEXT>
two omaha indians their eyes filled 
with tears became the first members of their tribe in 100 years to 
touch the sacred pole of the omaha tribe 
this occasion is very significant to me because my 
greatgreatgrandfather yellow smoke was the keeper of the sacred 
pole doran morris chairman of the omaha tribal council said at 
the ceremony at harvard university 
he and edward cline tribal planner for the omahas came from 
nebraska to harvards peabody museum to touch the pole monday and 
negotiate for its return 
morris said the pole is about 200 years old and was entrusted to 
the peabody by yellow smoke because he did not believe the younger 
generation of omahas would cherish it 
the pole more than five feet long is made of cottonwood and 
ash a human scalp is at one end 
i have been talking to my people and they feel we need to 
bring the sacred pole home to unite us as a tribe morris said 
it is the consensus of our people both the young and the old 
he said there are about 5000 people in the tribe 2400 of them 
on the reservation 
this pole is a living tree a living person as far as we are 
concerned cline said it was there for the people to see to 
be part of to touch and to keep the tribe together 
the object embodies so much of the soul of the omaha said 
ian w brown the peabodys associate curator of north american 
collections it represents the authority of their leaders the 
unity between man and woman and the binding element that has held 
the omaha people together for centuries 
