<TEXT>
luxury automaker rollsroyce may like to carry 
its passengers in style over the highways of life but it doesnt 
want people to mistakenly think it takes family pets into the 
hereafter 
the british company is challenging a logo used by a company that 
makes caskets and burial kits for pets 
rollsroyce has filed documents with the us patent office in 
washington alleging that pet rest inc owned by mike and sandy 
mccormack has adopted a logo confusingly close to its own 
pet rests logo includes a capital p and an interlocking capital 
r rollsroyce said it has used two interlocking capital rs to 
identify its company since 1925 
literally i sat down with a tablet and drew variations of the 
letters p and r sidebyside up and down and interlocking 
mccormack said we tried to find any way that the letters could 
work well together in a logo it was by chance that we selected the 
one we use today 
the mccormacks founded their business three years ago in lima 
about 75 south of toledo mrs mccormack said the burial kits 
include satinlined burial capsules suggestions for a memorial 
service and even grief counseling prices range from 80 to 1499 
and kits can accommodate pets as large as a doberman pinscher 
the company could gross up to 1 million this year the 
mccormacks said 
mrs mccormack learned of the challenge from rollsroyce this 
month by registered letter 
it was very surprising she said we were just astounded 
that anyone could confuse a rollsroyce product with a pet rest 
product 
she said the pr logo is not stamped on the burial kits but is 
used on boxes and in advertising 
attorneys for rollsroyce declined to comment but in documents 
filed with the appeals board the attorneys argue that the 
similarity of the trademarks might give rise to a mistaken belief 
that pet rests products originate from or are sponsored by 
rollsroyce 
the mccormacks plan to fight at least for now 
rather than come on with a lawsuit against a small company 
like ours theyll just fight the trademark year after year with 
the hope that after five years and perhaps 25000 if we can even 
afford to drag it on that long we will give up mrs mccormack 
said 
