<TEXT>
nazi hunters on tuesday handed the british 
government a list of 13 alleged war criminals who fled to britain 
saying it was new evidence the country harbored nazi collaborators 
to assist with antisoviet intelligence 
rabbi marvin hier of the nazihunting simon wiesenthal center 
submitted the list of white russians now aged 63 to 89 to a 
twoman legal panel appointed by the government the list showed 
all but three were policemen 
the home office said it will try to trace the men on the list 
which brings to 31 the number of suspects submitted to the panel by 
the los angelesbased wiesenthal center 
the panel also has received from other sources the names of 84 
other suspected nazi collaborators of which 18 have been traced to 
british addresses 
hier said researchers stumbled on the new list last week while 
sifting through british government records for traces of members of 
adolf hitlers notorious ss who escaped to canada via britain after 
world war ii 
hier said some of the suspects addresses in british prisoner of 
war camps were first submitted by the soviet ambassador in november 
1947 
the soviet sheet of charges showed most of the 13 were accused 
of taking part in mass murders and deportations in nazioccupied 
soviet territory in 1941 and 1942 
but the researchers found a december 1947 reply from ernest 
bevin the foreign secretary in britains first postwar 
government telling the soviet ambassador that none of the men 
could be traced despite an exhaustive search 
this is incredible said hier in london to hand over the 
evidence 
the soviet embassy provided specific details of what each and 
every one of these men had done and where they were down to post 
box and street numbers and the british in their own country 
couldnt find them hier said in an interview 
hier gave a photocopy of the list to the associated press with 
the names blanked out the centers usual policy is to release 
names only to government investigators 
the wiesenthal center which has long accused britain of 
footdragging over fugitive nazis and their collaborators also 
produced a 1983 letter from prime minister margaret thatchers 
government saying britain has not felt obliged to deport suspected 
war criminals since 1950 
now we know why inquiries made about nazi war criminals from 
the beginning were left hanging said hier it was the cold war 
and they were interested in countering communism they wanted to 
play ball with the nazi criminals 
