case with the interstate commerce commission to force united parcel 
service to deliver class c fireworks to customers in other states 
the icc board voted 32 on monday to strike down a ups policy 
that permitted it to refuse to ship fireworks on grounds that too 
many states have conflicting regulations on fireworks shipment 
the icc order reverses an earlier decision to uphold the 
delivery service policy in late 1987 
bob kenney a ups spokesman said it was too early to comment 
richard streeter a lawyer for bj alan of youngstown and 24 
other fireworks companies in the case said the ruling would force 
ups to resume delivery to outofstate customers because the 
service is a common carrier holding a virtual monopoly on 
inexpensive parcel delivery to homes 
when they ups pulled the plug there was no reasonable 
alternative for the fireworks companies federal express was the 
only thing that saved the companies but they were just too 
expensive for most customers 
he said federal express would charge about 25 for a parcel of 
fireworks that could be delivered for 5 or 6 by ups 
he said the shipping ban extended only to fireworks and none of 
the other 34 categories of class c explosives including ammunition 
and explosive rivets 
