<TEXT>
romania ordered the immediate closure of 
a hungarian consulate on tuesday and expelled the consular staff 
the hungarian state news agency mti reported in a widening rift 
between the two communist neighbors 
the action was unprecedented in recent soviet bloc diplomatic 
history romania and hungary are military allies in the sovietled 
warsaw pact 
the decision to close the hungarian general consulate in 
clujnapoca was apparently prompted by a demonstration of about 
50000 hungarians in budapest monday night to protest a project 
calling for demolition of 7000 romanian villages including ethnic 
hungarian communities by the year 2000 
clujnapoca is a city in transylvania in northwestern romania 
where most of the 17 million ethnic hungarians live hungarians 
know it as kolozsvar 
ethnic hungarians have long complained about alleged 
discrimination and denial of ethnic rights they form the largest 
minority group in east europe outside the soviet union 
mti said foreign minister ioan totu called in hungarian 
ambassador pal szucs on tuesday and told him romania considers 
operation of the consulate as terminated with immediate effect 
according to mti romania demanded that the staff leave the 
territory of romania within 48 hours 
romanian president nicolae ceausescu on tuesday rejected all 
criticism of his village demolition program and accused hungarian 
authorities of actively supporting the unofficial protest 
in a speech to the romanian communist partys central committee 
in bucharest ceausescu hinted that he may direct the hungarian 
embassy in budapest to scale down operations following the protest 
rally 
the resettlement plan calls for 7000 of romanias 13000 
villages to be torn down and replaced with agriculturalindustrial 
centers romanian staterun media said the goal is to gain more 
farmland for use by the countrys collectivized agriculture which 
is plagued by lack of incentives for farmers and livestock fodder 
shortages 
the protesters monday night filed quietly past the romanian 
embassy in the biggest unofficial rally in hungary since the 1956 
hungarian uprising police did not interfere 
the hungarian government newspaper magyar hirlap on tuesday 
praised the marchers discipline 
but ceausescu denounced new actions of a chauvinistic 
nationalistic antiromanian antisocialist nature in hungary 
he told the party meeting yesterday a new manifestation was 
organized with the agreement and as stated even by news coming 
from hungary under the aegis of the official party and state 
bodies of hungary the state news agency agerpres reported 
as reported by agerpres ceausescu also sought to depict the 
growing chorus of hungarian protests as means to make people forget 
about hungarys serious economic problems 
the mti agency said responsibility for violating the consular 
agreement lies with romania it added that this severe romanian 
measure will not divert hungary from its principled policy 
aimed at deepening friendship between the hungarian and romanian 
peoples strengthening the connecting role of the nationalities 
living in their countries 
both the hungarian government and speakers at mondays rally 
made it clear that a change of existing borders is out of the 
question under the 1920 trianon treaty predominantly hungarian 
transylvania became part of romania 
hungarys premier and communist party chief karoly grosz is 
scheduled to visit romania probably in late summer 
ceausescu said issues between the two parties and countries must 
be solved exclusively by way of talks in a spirit of equality 
respect and noninterference in the domestic affairs of either 
country 
