<DOCNO> AP880628-0221 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
many defense contractors did a slipshod job of 
protecting classified information according to a pentagon study 
that thendefense secretary caspar weinberger tried to withhold 
from congress last year sources say 
the study by the defense investigative service found that only 
10 percent of the contractors surveyed had no deficiencies in the 
way they handled classified information related to special access 
programs the highest level of secrecy and more than half fell 
into categories that were either unsatisfactory or 
exceedingly serious 
the 80page report was done in response to a congressional 
demand in the wake of reports that lockheed one of the nations 
biggest defense contractors couldnt account for 1400 documents 
relating to the topsecret stealth airplane 
the dis study is not directly related to the current criminal 
investigation of the pentagon and defense contractors that probe 
centers on allegations that defense contractors and consultants 
many of whom are former military men bribed pentagon officials for 
information crucial to winning contracts worth billions of dollars 
the report is itself classified and has not been publicly 
released but its contents were described by sources who had access 
to the document 
the study was finished in april 1987 but weinberger refused to 
send it to capitol hill until last october 2 hours before a house 
panels vote to subpoena the document the sources said 
instead weinberger sent a june 17 1987 letter noting the 
study was finished and describing what he said were its contents 
weinberger wrote that security of classified information was 
outstanding in some contractors satisfactory in the vast 
majority and unsatisfactory in a few contractor locations 
the study painted a far different picture the sources said 
attempts to reach weinberger for an explanation were 
unsuccessful he did not return telephone calls to his law office 
seeking comment 
the study looked at 101 different programs at 603 contractor 
sites the sources said many of the facilities worked on more than 
one classified program 
the dis created five categories for assessing how contractors 
handled the highly classified data the lowest was unsatisfactory 
next lowest was major deficiencies then came letter of 
requirement which meant problems were discovered that had to be 
corrected with the remedies confirmed in writing secondbest was 
corrected on the spot and the best was no deficiencies the 
sources said 
only 10 percent of the contractors had no deficiencies the 
sources said six percent were rated unsatisfactory 47 percent had 
major deficiencies 34 percent had letter of requirement 
deficiencies and 3 percent had problems that were corrected on the 
spot 
weinbergers letter may have used some semantical logic by 
counting anyone who ranked above the lowest dis grade of 
unsatisfactory when he said security was satisfactory in 
the vast majority of contractor sites but that also would entail 
using the word satisfactory in regard to contractors whose 
deficiencies the dis itself labeled as exceedingly serious 
in the report the dis defined major deficiencies the grade 
given the largest group of contractors as deficiencies which 
were exceedingly serious and which resulted in the compromise of 
classified information or which could have logically led to a 
compromise if not properly corrected 
according to dis unsatisfactory meant the contractor 
appears to be either unwilling or unable to take prompt corrective 
action to safeguard classified information which appears to be in 
imminent danger 
weinberger has defended his pentagon tenure saying he wasnt 
responsible for abuses which occurred while he was defense 
secretary i dont have any basis whatever for saying i didnt do 
enough and i certainly dont feel culpableweinberger said 
sunday on an abctv show 
but rep john dingell dmich chairman of the house energy and 
commerce committee said on the same show we warned mr 
weinberger there were problems in the way contractors handled 
classified information 
between 1984 and 1986 the energy and commerce investigations 
subcommittee held 17 public hearings on defense contractors many 
of them focusing on specific weapons and contractors subcommittee 
records show 
the dis study originated in august 1986 when rep ron wyden 
dore won approval of an amendment to the fiscal 1987 budget bill 
requiring the review wyden is the ranking democrat on the 
subcommittee 
wyden said he wasnt satisfied by weinbergers june 17 letter 
because our subcommittee had been investigating this issue and 
his letter just didnt feel right i felt it was a whitewash and 
then we heard from some people over in the pentagon that 
weinbergers letter was far different from what the dis report 
said 
the dis report wasnt sent to capitol hill until oct 2 hours 
before the subcommittee was scheduled to vote on whether to try to 
subpoena the report the panel went ahead anyway and voted for the 
subpoena but the action was never ratified by the full committee 
or house because the report had already been sent wyden noted 
</TEXT>
