<TEXT>
legislation requiring that fishing vessels 
carry such safety equipment as life rafts and survival suits was 
approved tuesday by the house capping a threeyear effort by 
northwest lawmakers who called the measure a memorial to those who 
have died at sea 
this was an important firststep in making the industry 
safer said robert barry whose son died when the fishing vessel 
western sea sank off the alaska coast in 1985 
barry who lives in washington dc said the 70yearold 
western sea which was registered out of seattle did not contain 
life rafts survival suits or an emergency locator when it went 
down with six crewmen aboard 
the crew of the western sea would have had a chance of 
surviving if they had had such things as life rafts said barry 
without them they didnt have a chance 
barry and his wife peggy lobbied hard for passage of the bill 
but added that more needs to be done including mandatory training 
of fishing boat crews and mandatory coast guard inspections the 
bill now goes to the senate 
it seems strange to me that men and women have died because 
they literally did not know how to open a pressurized life raft 
said mrs barry 
the bill specifically requires that fishing boats carry radio 
communications equipment including an emergency positionindicating 
radio beacon in addition boats must carry life rafts or lifeboats 
for each crew member and passenger and enough survival suits to 
enable them to survive for at least four hours in the water 
rep john miller rwash a cosponsor of the bill said the 
measure should assure the families who have lost their loved ones 
that we have heard their anguish and listened to their plea that 
others be spared 
the bill will not return loved ones lost at sea miller said 
in a floor statement but it is a lasting and fitting memorial to 
the men and women young and old who did not return home from 
fishing 
about 250 us fishing boats sink each year according to coast 
guard statistics 
rep mike lowry dwash another bill cosponsor said the 
death rate for fishermen is seven times the national average and 
twice that among miners the next most hazardous profession 
an alarming number of people have been killed in accidents on 
commercial fishing boats said lowry we cant allow this 
dangerous situation to continue 
saying that about 80 fishermen die every year in accidents 
involving commercial fishing boats lowry added the legislation 
will go a long way toward preventing these tragic accidents 
stripped from the bill was a provision that would have limited 
the liability of boat owners in the case of accidents 
the insurance provision strongly opposed by the trial lawyers 
lobby and some consumer groups had led to the defeat of the bill 
on the house floor during the previous session of congress miller 
also said lawmakers had to overcome considerable skepticism from 
the fishing industry over the need for the measure 
the fishing industry has this macho aura and are very 
skeptical of regulations miller said in an interview they 
feel they are masters of the sea 
