<TEXT>
alexander dubcek ousted by the soviets after they crushed his 
prague spring liberalization movement in 1968 lives today in the 
seclusion of a villa overlooking bratislava capital of his native 
slovakia 
officially he is a retired forestry clerk 
dubcek was arrested after the sovietled invasion of august 1968 
but released and allowed to remain on in his post as 
czechoslovakias communist party leader 
from then on it was an escalator ride to oblivion 
april 1969 he is removed as party leader and named president 
of parliament a largely ceremonial post 
september in a purge of the party central committee he is 
fired as parliament president 
december dubcek is named ambassador to turkey 
march 1970 he is suspended from the communist party 
june he is formally expelled from the communist party and 
called home from turkey 
july dubcek is recalled as a deputy in parliaments house of 
the people his last remaining official post he and his wife 
anna move into political exile in slovakia where he is given a 
job as a clerk in a forestry office 
from then on little is known except that dubcek now 66 years 
old is retired from his forestry job 
he and his family are said to have been kept under close 
surveillance until mikhail s gorbachev the reformist soviet 
leader visited czechoslovakia in april 1987 
he made a few trips to prague this year and on one occasion was 
loudly applauded when he attended a theater performance 
however an attempt earlier this year by dubcek and some other 
communist leaders from the prague spring to found an alternative 
political grouping was repressed 
</TEXT>
