the closing of an old garbage incinerator tuesday 
raised the prospect that up to 200 daily overseas flights into 
torontos international airport soon may have to fly without food 
for passengers 
under canadian government regulations garbage from incoming 
international flights must be incinerated to prevent the 
importation of disease 
but the old toronto incinerator used for that purpose closed 
tuesday because of fears that it was spewing dioxins and other 
pollutants into the air 
temporary disposal facilities at the airport may be ready in 
about four weeks but in the interim the 52 airlines using toronto 
airport have been unable to find a place to burn 25 tons a day of 
waste said transport canada spokesman ian taylor 
the executive committee of the metropolitan toronto council 
agreed tuesday night to keep the old incinerator open at least for 
a few days to avert a crisis on wednesday 
earlier taylor had said that without the incinerator 
well have nowhere to store the garbage and nowhere to 
incinerate it he said the airlines have said that as a last 
resort they may have to withdraw food service its a major 
problem 
a spokesman for minneapolisbased northwest airlines whose only 
direct flight into toronto is from detroit said his airline will 
simply take any garbage from the short flight back to detroit 
airlines making stopovers at other airports can empty their 
garbage there 
but carriers operating longer direct flights serving two or 
three meals have no such solution 
you cant fly airplanes around full of garbage said 
spokesman barry corbett of the canadian airline wardair which has 
regular service between toronto and london paris and honolulu 
it would only take a day or so and your plane would be full of 
garbage with no room for baggage we believe this is resolvable 
somehow before that happens corbett said 
the airlines had hoped to ship the waste to a new incinerator in 
hamilton an hour south of toronto by road but hamilton officials 
announced june 22 they will not take the garbage unless airlines 
schedule more flights to their city a sore point in a steel town 
jealous of torontos economic dominance 
as a stopgap taylor said the government will allow the 
airlines to install compacting and dehydration machines at the 
airport to turn the waste into odorless pellets the pellets can 
then be stored in an airport building until a permanent solution is 
found he said 
but that equipment cant be up and running for about four 
weeks he added 
other canadian airports have their own incinerators operated by 
the airlines but toronto residents objected to a similar proposal 
here 
