<DOCNO> AP880628-0304 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the staff of the nuclear regulatory commission 
unveiled a proposal monday aimed at making it easier to license new 
nuclear plants and warned that no one will ever build one again 
unless something like it is adopted 
under the proposal the commission could grant a conditional 
operating license at the same time it grants a construction permit 
provided that the plant design conformed with previously tested and 
approved models 
the nrc still would have to decide when construction was 
complete if the conditions for operation had been met but the 
procedure would entail far less time and effort than the current 
licensing system in which some plants have remained idle for years 
even after construction was complete 
the draft regulation would sharply restrict the required public 
hearings on operating licenses to allegations of material and 
uncorrected nonconformance with the conditional license or 
allegations that adequate protection is threatened 
the commission has long sought congressional authority to grant 
the operating license and the construction permit at the same time 
for standardized plants but various bills to encourage 
standardization and allow such onestop licensing have not 
gotten beyond the hearing stage 
in presenting the regulatory proposal william c parler the 
nrcs general counsel told the commissioners it is my judgment 
that unless the licensing process is changed it is not likely to 
be used by people who have to make the decisions about obtaining 
bulk power supply in the future 
utility executives have voiced similar sentiments for years 
commission chairman lando zech said he hoped to publish the 
proposal for public comment soon he said it was perhaps the most 
important initiative we are engaged in this year 
loring mills vice president for nuclear matters at the edison 
electric institute the nations principal trade association of 
private utilities said later we are in favor of whatever the 
nrc can do administratively to move forward on standardized plant 
design and onestop licensing 
though 107 commercial plants provide more than 18 percent of the 
nations electricity huge construction costs delays and 
controversy over safety have meant no new plant orders since the 
1970s 
the 107 plants encompass more than 60 reactor designs from five 
providers and built by more than a dozen engineering companies at 
connecticuts millstone plant three different builders provided 
reactors 
standard designs to which modifications are strictly limited are 
bound to save costs make operation easier and facilitate the 
transfer of expertise and safety information from one operator to 
another the commission believes 
the new plan would permit utilities to win approval for a site 
in advance of approval of plant design with such authorization 
good for 20 years to permit banking of sites 
the commission would also certify standard plant designs as 
safe normally after operation of a demonstration reactor 
according to the draft regulation the site application 
shall contain emergency plans which are as fully developed as 
circumstances permit and which show that the area surrounding the 
site is amenable to emergency planning which would provide 
reasonable assurance that adequate protective measures could be 
taken in the even of a radiological emergency at the site 
the construction application would require a showing that the 
utility had made a good faith effort to win approval of 
emergency plans by local and state governments 
refusal by the state and local governments to cooperate in an 
evacuation plan has kept the shoreham plant on long island from 
winning an operating license and similar objections by 
massachusetts have kept the seabrook plant just over the border on 
new hampshires seacoast from operating 
the commission insists as a general matter that it can license 
plants in such circumstances and to require state and local 
approval would give those authorities a veto that congress never 
intended 
under the proposed plan a utility failing to get that 
cooperation would still have to show that its proposed emergency 
plans nonetheless provide reasonable assurance that adequate 
protective measures can be taken in the event of a radiological 
emergency at the site 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

